{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17515917","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17515917"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:36:39+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:36:39+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12521"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12521","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12521"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.14,0.15,0.06,0.58,0.07]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5022"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"95805"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5022","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5022"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12521"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"78584"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"6"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"404"},{"type":"tags","id":"1132"},{"type":"tags","id":"1206"},{"type":"tags","id":"4974"},{"type":"tags","id":"4977"},{"type":"tags","id":"6275"},{"type":"tags","id":"11626"},{"type":"tags","id":"11633"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8341"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8660"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26721"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30411"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30434"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42773"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43339"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"95805","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/95805"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 72-year-old man is brought by ambulance to the Emergency Department after a fall at home. The fall happened two hours ago after slipping on his wet kitchen floor, landing on his left side and being unable to get up independently. His daughter came home an hour later to find him on the floor and called an ambulance. According to the patient, there was no head trauma and no loss of consciousness, but he has significant pain in his left groin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHe has a history of hypertension, currently well-controlled on amlodipine.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, his heart rate is 89/min, blood pressure 130/80 mmHg, respiratory rate 19/min, SpO\u003Csub\u003E2\u003C/sub\u003E 97% on room air, and temperature 37.0\u00b0C. His left leg is shortened with his knee pointing outwards. His left leg range of motion is significantly limited due to pain.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn X-ray of his pelvis is shown (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Pertrochanteric fracture","Anterior hip dislocation","Acetabular fracture","Subcapital femur fracture","Greater trochanteric fracture"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has a \u003Cstrong\u003Esubcapital femur fracture\u003C/strong\u003E, which is a type of femoral neck fracture located just below the head of the femur. This should be suspected in elderly patients who have had a fall and present with groin pain, decreased range of motion of the hip, and an externally rotated and shortened leg. X-ray is the initial and most effective form of diagnostic imaging. For children and adults below 60 years of age with a non-displaced fracture, the surgical technique in management is usually open reduction and internal fixation (ORIF). However, for older patients with a displaced fracture, they will usually require primary hip arthroplasty (hemi/total).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPertrochanteric fracture\u003C/strong\u003E occurs through the intertrochanteric line of the femur, between the greater and lesser trochanters. Pertrochanteric femoral fractures are a subtype of trochanteric fractures involving the femur. They can involve both the greater and lesser trochanter and are a type of extracapsular fracture. While they are also common in elderly patients after falls, the fracture line would be visible in a different location on X-ray, further down from the femoral head compared to a subcapital fracture.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn \u003Cstrong\u003Eanterior hip dislocation\u003C/strong\u003E is less common than posterior dislocation and typically results in external rotation and abduction of the leg, but it is usually associated with high-energy trauma, which is not consistent with this patient\u0027s low-energy fall.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn \u003Cstrong\u003Eacetabular fracture\u003C/strong\u003E involves the socket of the hip joint and is often associated with high-impact trauma. It would present with significant pain and possibly instability of the hip joint, but the X-ray would show a fracture line through the acetabulum, which is not the case here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Egreater trochanteric fracture\u003C/strong\u003E involves the bony prominence on the femur where the gluteal muscles attach. It can cause pain and difficulty with hip movement, but typically does not cause significant leg shortening or external rotation. The X-ray would show a fracture at the greater trochanter, which is not indicated here.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Subcapital femur fractures are a type of neck of femur fracture located just below the femoral head, commonly seen in elderly patients after falls.","Clinical signs of femoral neck fractures include groin pain, shortened and externally rotated leg, and decreased range of motion.","X-ray is the initial diagnostic imaging modality for suspected hip fractures."],"references":["Lu Y, Uppal HS. Hip Fractures: Relevant Anatomy, Classification, and Biomechanics of Fracture and Fixation. Geriatr Orthop Surg Rehabil. 2019 Jul 3;10:2151459319859139. doi: 10.1177/2151459319859139. PMID: 31321116; PMCID: PMC6610445. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/31321116/","Kazley JM, Banerjee S, Abousayed MM, Rosenbaum AJ. Classifications in Brief: Garden Classification of Femoral Neck Fractures. Clin Orthop Relat Res. 2018 Feb;476(2):441-445. doi: 10.1007/s11999.0000000000000066. PMID: 29389800; PMCID: PMC6259691. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/29389800/","Kazley J, Bagchi K. Femoral Neck Fractures. [Updated 2023 May 8]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2025 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK537347/","Jones, J. Pertrochanteric fracture. Radiopaedia [Internet webpage]. Sept 2021. Available at: https://radiopaedia.org/articles/pertrochanteric-fracture"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"78584"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12521"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"19657"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"19657","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/19657"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/4c9fbc93-7f87-4793-add7-c0e23495cefd.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/4c9fbc93-7f87-4793-add7-c0e23495cefd.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":768,"height":552}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"78584","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/78584"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-29T20:14:20+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-30T15:06:33+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5022"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"95805"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"6","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/6"},"attribut